\contentsline {table}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Evaluation platform. All prove-mode measurements are local single-machine runs with no network or dev-mode acceleration unless stated.}}{62}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces PLUM single-signature verification, prove mode, $\lambda =80$, M5~Pro 24~GB. \emph {Cell~1} (no precompile), \emph {Cell~2} (Griffin-$\mathbb {F}_p^{192}$ precompile), and \emph {Cell~3} (software SHA-3 control) name the three SP1 arms throughout; Cell~2 and Cell~3 are means of three fixed-config runs (\S \ref {ssec:headline}), and the SHA-3 arm is a control, not a deployable PLUM variant. $^\dag $$14.25$~min mean (range $14.05$--$14.61$, ${\approx }14.2$~GB peak RSS). $^\ddag $RISC~Zero receipt verified; verify wall-clock not separately logged.}}{63}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {3}{\ignorespaces Aurora over a single Loquat-verification R1CS ($\mathbb {F}_{p^2}$, $127$-bit base)~\cite {10.1007/978-981-96-0957-4_3}, M5~Pro 24~GB; mean of three solo runs, per-run range in parentheses (records in \texttt {docs/measurements/pub\_hardening\_20260610}). Prover time includes Aurora setup, not recompile time (\S \ref {ssec:churn-eval}). Achieved $107.5$-bit security (below the $128$ target); \texttt {ACCEPT} every run.}}{65}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces Same-scheme substrate comparison: one Loquat verification, $\lambda =80$, M5~Pro 24~GB, three solo runs per leg, neither zero-knowledge. Aurora leg $=$ mean of Table~\ref {tab:aurora-ref}; SP1 leg $=$ range of three runs ($44.4$/$47.4$/$64.0$~min) under the reduced-memory config (\S \ref {ssec:settings-justify}), succinct core STARK. Only the substrate differs; the $12$--$17\times $ gap is the zkVM's cost for this scheme. Isolates the substrate for \emph {Loquat}; does not transfer to PLUM (no $127$-bit Aurora harness).}}{66}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces Cycle-level cost attribution, PLUM verification, SHA-3 hasher, $\lambda =128$, \emph {execute mode}. Routing field arithmetic through the host precompile (and removing redundant reductions) cuts $37.9\%$ of SP1 cycles and $70.5\%$ of RISC~Zero cycles; RISC~Zero's larger reduction reflects its heavier per-multiplication baseline emulation ($6{,}625$ cycles/mul at baseline, falling to $1{,}826$ with the precompile path, against SP1's baseline of about $2{,}567$ cycles/mul).}}{67}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {6}{\ignorespaces Credential relations, $\lambda =80$, M5~Pro 24~GB. On RISC~Zero, execute mode validates CreGen's honest path ($9.4\times 10^{9}$ cycles); its succinct prove yielded no receipt (internal-verifier rejection, not a resource limit; \S \ref {ssec:cregen-anomaly}). On SP1 both relations complete a \emph {succinct} (non-ZK) prove: CreGen $26.98$/$31.11$~min, ShowCre $40.15$/$44.24$~min at $k{=}1$ and $58.14$~min at $k{=}2$---the $k{=}2$ within ${\approx }3.3\%$ of the additive-model projection (records \texttt {pub\_hardening\_20260611}, \texttt {audit5\_campaign\_20260612}).}}{68}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces Proof-mode feasibility matrix. Of the modes the zkVMs \emph {produce} on the target hardware, none is dependably zero-knowledge: SP1's rows are not ZK, RISC~Zero's receipt carries no formal ZK guarantee, and the only ZK mode the toolchain exposes (row~3, a pairing wrap) is neither post-quantum nor shipped by default---the dual obstruction; the one ZK proof produced here is the static Aurora run (last row, \S \ref {ssec:aurora-ref}). \textsuperscript {$\dagger $}zk-enabled Aurora now measured, the zk-disabled row kept for comparison (both $107.5$ bits, below $\lambda =128$). \textsuperscript {$\ddagger $}RISC~Zero's receipt has ZK blinding but the vendor disclaims a formal guarantee, so we treat it as not dependably ZK~\cite {risc0zkadvisory,l2beatzk} (Section~\ref {sec:security}).}}{103}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces Circuit/parameter regeneration footprint ($N_{\mathsf {circ}},N_{\mathsf {param}}$; Definition~\ref {def:update-churn}). The static regime regenerates and re-audits its R1CS and constraint-dependent parameters on every localised change; the zkVM absorbs a change as a guest edit ($N_{\mathsf {circ}}{=}N_{\mathsf {param}}{=}0$), except across the precompile boundary. \textsuperscript {$\ast $}The Loquat$\to $PLUM swap moves the hash field ($\mathbb {F}_{p^2}$ 127-bit $\to $ 199-bit $\mathbb {F}_p$), regenerating the field-specific Griffin AIR. $N_{\mathsf {src}},N_{\mathsf {audit}}$ in prose below.}}{104}{}%
\contentsline {table}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces Per-change recompile components for a non-preprocessing (Aurora) versus a preprocessing (Fractal) argument on the same $127$-bit harness, M5~Pro 24~GB. The $2^{10}$--$2^{14}$ rows are synthetic R1CS; the $2^{19}$ row is the single-Loquat-verification (BDEC building-block) size. Aurora has no per-circuit indexer ($R_{\mathsf {static}}$ sub-second); Fractal's indexer is superlinear and OOMs at $2^{19}$. The zkVM regenerates no circuit.}}{104}{}%
